\subsubsection{Research} Research  is the systematic inquiry (i.e., there is a plan) into the study of (in our case social) situations to establish facts and either reaffirm previous work or reach a new conclusion.  For example, since 1950, social researchers have found a relationship between the degree of poverty in a neighborhood and the difficulty of maintaining social order in the affected communities. 

\subsubsection{Data science}  Data science is the systemic study of structure and behavior of collecting, organizing, evaluating, and interpreting data.  The interpretation phase refers to the population characteristics from sampling. For example, we define the research question, what data to collect, how to analyze the data, report the results. 

\subsubsection{{Data}} Data are information collected from a population for further analysis.  For example, the General Social Survey (GSS) is a survey that collects data of attitudes, concerns, experiences, and has become a repository of  societal changes of United States residents.

\subsubsection{Theory}  The theory is a statement used to explain a situation, e.g.,  is there a difference between alcohol awareness  among health and safety class and a statistics class among college students, or contemplate this question: What causes poverty?  There are many possibilities, but let's consider:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item personal traits (laziness), or
  \item structural failing (not enough jobs).
  \end{itemize}
  
These examples show the richness of social science research.  Research involves measurements whether using a survey to sample a population about the upcoming election or obtaining the amount of lead in the drinking water of two nearby cities.  

\subsubsection{Hypothesis}  The hypothesis is an explanation for an association between events, e.g.,  alcohol awareness among college students is the same between students enrolled in a health and safety class and for those enrolled in a statistics course.  As we review our hypothesis, we will continue the research process by considering the following step:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Who is the population,
  \item How many cases do we need to study this population (sample size),
  \item What measurements do we need to take to answer our question, and
  \item many other related issues.
\end{itemize}  

\subsubsection{Observations}  Observations are the collected data to test a hypothesis, e.g., a random sample (RS) \footnote{RS is a sample where we select each subject with an equal chance from the population.} of sophomores registered for  a health and safety class and those enrolled in a statistics course which surveys alcohol awareness.  Observations requires the following:
\begin{itemize}
  \item planning: 
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Who, What, Where, Why, When, and How.
  \end{itemize}  
  \item implementation: 
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Collecting, Storing, Retrieving,  Analyzing, and, Reporting.  
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}  

So why is this process necessary, let's suppose that there are 50 cases in the control group and 50 cases in the test group.  Each case answers 11 questions.  There are 1,100 pieces of data to collect, store, retrieve, analyze, and report.  Therefore, it is necessary to be organized while doing research. 


\subsubsection{Empirical Generalizations}  Empirical generalizations are made to assess the theory after analyzing and interpretation of the data, e.g., research on alcohol understanding among college students published a higher awareness for students enrolled in a health and safety college course than for those enrolled in a college statistics course.
\begin{itemize}
  \item interpretation of the data, and 
  \item conclusion: Did the data support our hypothesis. 
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Variables and Cases}

\subsubsection{Variables}

\begin{itemize}
\item Variables are attributes of a person (case).
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Examples: socio-economic statistics such as age, gender, race, and social class.
  \end{itemize}

\item Theories and hypotheses are asserting the association between variables.
  \begin{itemize}
  \item A belief may identify some variables as causes (independent variables) and others as effects or results (dependent variable).
  \end{itemize}

\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Case}

\begin{itemize}
\item The case is a collection of variables from a person (entity).
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Cases are from groups; for example, members from churches or unions or cities or states.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

