\section{Types of Statistics}


\subsection{Descriptive Statistics}

Descriptive statistics are used to explain the basic features of the data in a study.

There are three methods of describing data.

\begin{enumerate}
\item When we summarize {\bf{one variable at a time}}, we call that {\bf{Univariate}} descriptive statistics:
	\begin{itemize}
	\item The average IQ of the class is 120,  also range, variance, etc. 
	\item The percent of females taking Stat 2830 this semester is 55 percent.
	\end{itemize}

\item When we summarize {\bf{two variables at a time}}, we call that {\bf{Bivariate}} descriptive statistics, such as 
looking for relationships between two variables that describe strength and direction.
	\begin{itemize}
	\item The relationship between age and happiness.
	\item The association between income and food insecurity.
	\end{itemize}	

\item When we summarize {\bf{three or more variables at a time}}, we call that {\bf{Multivariate}} descriptive statistics, such as looking for relationships among three or more variables that describe strength and direction.
	\begin{itemize}
	\item Anonymous sources say that conspicuous consumption is a way for men to show their status to other males.  
	\item A recent study looked at the changes in testosterone level in response to changes in his status created by 
	using a product such as an old car versus a new sports car.  The subjects of the study were told to drive 
	on a busy urban avenue or a less traveled rural highway.

	\end{itemize}	
\end{enumerate}


\subsection{Inferential Statistics}

Inferential statistics makes a general statement about a population based on a sample selected from that population.

