\begin{itemize}
\item Population (P) contains all cases.  Usually, it is enormous which makes a complete enumeration of all values nearly impossible because of the budget, or other limitations.
\item Samples (S) are part of the population  and has a manageable size.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Inferential Statistics Example}

Since 1968, voter surveys use inferential statistics.

\begin{itemize}
\item The media (electronic and print) selects a random sample of the electorate about their voting preferences.
\item The results are used to estimate the voting preferences of all voters.
\item e.g., The Democrat candidate will receive about 48 percent of the vote in Kalamazoo County.
\end{itemize}

\section{Types of Data}
\subsection{Categorical (qualitative data)}

A categorical variable is a set of attributes that has two or more values, but there is no natural ordering to the values.  For example, zip code is a categorical variable having lots of categories (49001, 49008, 49009, etc.) and there is no intrinsic ordering of the values.  Eye color is also a categorical variable having a number of categories (black, blue, brown, hazal, etc.) and again, there is no agreed way to order these from highest to lowest.  A purely categorical variable is one that simply allows us to assign values (nominal), but we  cannot assign an order to the values. Whereas, categorical variable is one that simply allows us to assign values (ordinal), but we  can assign an order to the values.

\begin{itemize}
\item characteristics CANNOT be measured, but the researcher must count each instance.
\item e.g., gender, eye color, race, political affiliation, social status, etc.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Levels of Measurement for Categorical Data}

\begin{itemize}
\item Nominal categorical variable has no order:
	\begin{itemize}
	\item The scores are labels and ordering does not exist.
	\item e.g., gender, Social Security Number (SSN), the names of food pantries in Kalamazoo County.
	\end{itemize} 
\item The researcher can rank or categorize {\bf{ordinal categorical variables}}.
	\begin{itemize}
	\item The scores can be listed, and ordering does exist.
	\item e.g., The management structure of at city hall (mayor, department heads, etc.), class levels (freshman, sophomore, junior, and senior), social-economic status (poor, middle class, and rich).
	\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
		

\subsection{Numerical (quantitative data)}

\begin{itemize}
\item characteristics CAN be measured.
\item e.g., age, height, weight, number of students in this class, etc.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Levels of Measurement for Numerical Data}

\begin{itemize}

\item A numerical ratio  variable has a meaningful zero value, a proportion is allowed, and has magnitude.
	
		\begin{itemize}
		\item {\bf{Discrete}}
		\item the result of a counting process (whole number values)
		\item results of question ``how many?''
		\item e.g., the number of children per family.
		
		\item {\bf{Continuous}}
		
		\item there can be an infinite subdivision of scores (at least theoretically)
		\item e.g., age, time, distance to school.
		\end{itemize}

\item A numerical interval variable has magnitude, but the ratio does not make sense.
	\begin{itemize}
	\item e.g., GPA (a 4 point is not twice the value of a 2 point),  temperature (99 degrees is not three times as warm as 33 degrees).
	  
	\end{itemize} 	
	
\end{itemize}

